s1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 5:11\u8212?Paul availed himself of a legal provision and appealed to Caesar (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ai\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\i w11\u160?}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 12/15 5:30)\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li660 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [Inserted scripture.] Acts 25:11: If I am really a wrongdoer and have committed anything deserving of death, I do not beg off from dying; but if there is no substance to the accusations these men have made against me, no man has the right to hand me over to them as a favor. I appeal to Caesar!\u8221? [End of inserted scripture.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql \par{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Inserted Reference\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 5:8-12. Christians today can and should make use of available legal provisions \u8220?in the defending and legally establishing of the good news.\u8221?\u8212?}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Philippians 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 :7.\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [End of inserted reference material or article.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 6:1-3\u8212?Paul gave a skillful defense before King Herod Agrippa (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ai\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\i bt}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 -E 198-201 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 paragraphs 10-16}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 )\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li660 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [Inserted scripture.] Acts 26:1-3: Agrippa said to Paul: \u8220?You are permitted to speak in your own behalf.\u8221? Then Paul stretched out his hand and proceeded to say in his defense: \u8220?Concerning all the things of which I am accused by the Jews, King Agrippa, I consider myself happy that it is before you I am to make my defense this day, especially because you are an expert on all the customs as well as the controversies among the Jews. Therefore, I beg you to hear me patiently. [End of inserted scripture.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql \par\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Inserted Reference\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 10 Paul respectfully thanked King Agrippa for the opportunity to present a defense to him, acknowledging that the king was an expert on all the customs as well as the controversies among Jews. Paul then described his past life: \u8220?According to the strictest sect of our form of worship I lived a Pharisee.\u8221? (Acts 26:5) As a Pharisee, Paul had hoped in the coming of the Messiah. Now, as a Christian, he boldly identified Jesus Christ as that long-awaited one. A belief that he and his accusers had in common\u8212?that is, the hope of the fulfillment of God\u8217?s promise to their forefathers\u8212?was the reason that Paul was on trial that day. This situation left Agrippa even more interested in what Paul had to say.\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 11 Recalling his past outrageous treatment of Christians, Paul said: \u8220?I, for one, really thought within myself I ought to commit many acts of opposition against the name of Jesus the Nazarene .\u160?.\u160?. Since I was extremely mad against them [the followers of Christ], I went so far as to persecuting them even in outside cities.\u8221? (Acts 26:9-11) Paul was not exaggerating. Many people knew of the violence he had done to the Christians. (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Galatians 1:13, 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 3) \u8216?What could have changed such a man?\u8217? Agrippa may have wondered.\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 12 Paul\u8217?s next words provided the answer: \u8220?As I was journeying to Damascus with authority and a commission from the chief priests, I saw at midday on the road, O\u160?king, a light beyond the brilliance of the sun flash from heaven about me and about those journeying with me. And when we had all fallen to the ground I heard a voice say to me in the Hebrew language, \u8216?Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me? To keep kicking against the goads makes it hard for you.\u8217? But I said, \u8216?Who are you, Lord?\u8217? And the Lord said, \u8216?I am Jesus, whom you are persecuting.\u8217?\u8221?\u8212?Acts 26:12-15.\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 13 Before this supernatural event, Paul had figuratively been \u8220?kicking against the goads.\u8221? Just as a beast of burden would injure itself unnecessarily by kicking against the sharp end of an oxgoad, Paul had hurt himself spiritually by resisting the will of God. By appearing to Paul on the road to Damascus, the resurrected Jesus caused this sincere but clearly misguided man to change his thinking.\u8212?}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 John 16:1, 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 .\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 14 Paul did indeed make drastic changes in his life. Addressing Agrippa, he said: \u8220?I did not become disobedient to the heavenly sight, but both to those in Damascus first and to those in Jerusalem, and over all the country of Judea, and to the nations I went bringing the message that they should repent and turn to God by doing works that befit repentance.\u8221? (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 26:19, 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 0) For years, Paul had been fulfilling the commission that Jesus Christ had given him in that midday vision. With what results? Those who responded to the good news that Paul preached repented of their immoral, dishonest conduct and turned to God. Such ones became good citizens, contributing to and showing respect for law and order.\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 15 Those benefits, however, meant nothing to Paul\u8217?s Jewish opposers. Paul said: \u8220?On account of these things Jews seized me in the temple and attempted to slay me. However, because I have obtained the help that is from God I continue to this day bearing witness to both small and great.\u8221?\u8212?}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 26:21, 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 2.\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 16 As true Christians, we must be \u8220?always ready to make a defense\u8221? of our faith. (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 1 Peter 3}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 :15) When speaking to judges and rulers about our beliefs, we may find it helpful to imitate the method Paul used in speaking to Agrippa and Festus. By respectfully telling them how Bible truths have changed lives for the better\u8212?our own life as well as the lives of those who respond to our message\u8212?we may touch the hearts of these high officials.\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [End of inserted reference material or article.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 6:28\u8212?Paul\u8217?s words had a profound effect on the king\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li660 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe103