33\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li660 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [Inserted scripture.] Acts 26:14: And when we had all fallen to the ground, I heard a voice say to me in the Hebrew language: \u8216?Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me? To keep kicking against the goads makes it hard for you.\u8217? [End of inserted scripture.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql \par{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Inserted Reference\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\fi-480\li480 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 kicking against the goads: A goad is a pointed rod used to urge on an animal. (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Judges 3}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 :31) The expression \u8220?to kick against the goads\u8221? is a proverb found in Greek literature. It is based on the image of a stubborn bull that resists the prodding of the goad by kicking against it, resulting in injury to the animal. Saul behaved in a similar manner before becoming a Christian. By fighting against Jesus\u8217? followers, who had the backing of Jehovah God, Paul risked causing serious injury to himself. (Compare }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Acts 5:38, 39; 1 Timothy 1:13, 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 4.) At }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Ecclesiastes 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 2:11, \u8220?oxgoads\u8221? are mentioned in a figurative sense, referring to a wise person\u8217?s words that move a listener to follow counsel.\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langf